## 5. Execution Model

### 5.1 Invocation Type

| Subcomponent     | Type                                                                      |
| ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| HTTP Server      | Event-driven (Node.js event loop); all route handlers are `async`         |
| WebSocket Server | Event-driven; `ws.on("message")`                                          |
| SignalingHub     | Synchronous relay inside WS message handler                               |
| Upload Handler   | Async; awaits multer disk write                                           |
| FfmpegManager    | Async; awaits child process exit via `Promise` wrapper                    |
| JobQueue         | Event-driven; triggered by `"extraction-complete"` events or `POST /jobs` |
| GrpcClient       | Async streaming; `AsyncIterator` wraps gRPC `ClientReadableStream`        |
| ExperimentDB     | Synchronous (better-sqlite3 is sync-only)                                 |

### 5.2 Trigger Conditions

| Trigger                                          | Consequence                                                       |
| ------------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Phone connects to WS, sends `join`               | SignalingHub creates/joins room                                   |
| Phone sends SDP offer                            | SignalingHub relays to desktop                                    |
| `POST /upload/:experimentId/:cameraId` completes | multer writes file → DB update → ffmpeg spawn                     |
| ffmpeg exits 0                                   | DB update → WS broadcast → `JobQueue.emit("extraction-complete")` |
| `POST /jobs` received                            | Job inserted to queue → `tryDispatch()`                           |
| `extraction-complete` event AND no active job    | `tryDispatch()` processes next queued job                         |
| gRPC stream message                              | WS broadcast to desktop                                           |

### 5.3 Concurrency Model

Node.js is single-threaded. All concurrency is through the event loop. `child_process.spawn` runs `ffmpeg` in a separate OS process (does not block the event loop). Multiple uploads can proceed in parallel (each is an independent multer write), but `ffmpeg` extraction jobs for the same experiment are serialised (camera 0 and camera 1 may run concurrently since they are independent).

The `JobQueue` is strictly serial: only one gRPC job active at a time.

### 5.4 Timing Model

There are no hard real-time constraints on this module. Latencies are:

- WebRTC signaling: < 500ms LAN round-trip (best-effort).
- Upload: 15–60 sec for 375 MB video over WiFi.
- ffmpeg extraction: 30–120 sec for 900 frames at 1080p (I/O bound).
- gRPC streaming: Python-bound; Node is not the bottleneck.
- WebSocket status events: < 10ms from gRPC message receipt to WS send.

